Data Collection

(Was done on the Tufts High Performance Cluster w/ 16 cores and 200 GB of memory)
- Weather Data
    - Use the open-mateo historical weather API
        - Select parameters for date range (1/1/2025 - 12/31/2025), location (Boston), hourly weather variables (precipitation), and use the resulting api link

- Train Arrival Data
  - Use the MBTA Blue Book Open Data for MBTA Rapid Transit Travel Times 2025 (https://mbta-massdot.opendata.arcgis.com/datasets/5f71a5c035fc4a4dad1b7fa73ba27ef8/about)
  - For our project, you only needed to use the LRT travel times, but trains.ipynb uses all train data

- Trains.ipynb (Part 1)
 -  Use this Jupyter notebook to merge the information on train arrival time with weather data, and put all this information into a parquet file

- theBigUnzip.ipynb
  - Get the links to zip files of the archive data from https://cdn.mbta.com/archive/archived_feeds.txt (would use equivalent schedule data if you were to analyze some other train system)
  - Put all the wanted archived schedule data into a parquet file

- Trains.ipynb (Part 2)
    - Merge the train arrival and weather data information with the archived schedule data
    - Calculate the difference between the scheduled arrival time and the actual arrival time
    - Create CSV file for data processing and modeling


Data Processing and Modeling
- Use the graphing.py file to process the resulting CSV files
      - Do the final processing of data for modeling (place rain amounts into buckets, place dates into seasons, and handle date overflow from calculating delays)
      - provides both exploratory results (to get graphs of the overall distribution of delay, and with initial parameters like season, amount of precipitation, and train line) 
      - Implements the scikit-learn Expectation-Maximization Gaussian Modeler to create a probabilistic model of our train delays
      - Creates final charts of the probabilistic model and compares the model to the initial dataset
        - Users can create models of the other trains besides the ones shown in the presenation

